# 🧠 LLM System Architecture – Complete Documentation

This repository documents a **production-grade Large Language Model (LLM) system architecture**, covering **all four core layers** used in modern GenAI applications:

1. Model Layer  
2. Retrieval Layer  
3. Orchestration Layer  
4. Application Layer  

The goal of this document is to explain **how real-world LLM systems are designed, built, and scaled**, and to serve as:
- 📘 Interview preparation material  
- 🏗️ System design reference  
- 📄 Project documentation  

---

## 📌 High-Level Architecture Overview

Modern LLM applications are **not just a model**. They are multi-layered systems designed to overcome the limitations of raw language models.

### End-to-End Flow
User Input
↓
Application Layer
↓
Orchestration Layer
↓
Retrieval Layer (optional)
↓
Model Layer
↓
Generated Response
↓
User

---

## 1️⃣ Model Layer (Core Intelligence)

### Purpose
The **Model Layer** is responsible for:
- Understanding natural language
- Reasoning over input
- Generating coherent responses

> This layer does **not** have access to private or real-time data by default.

---

### Internal Architecture
Most modern LLMs are based on the **Transformer architecture**, which includes:
- Tokenization
- Embedding layers
- Multi-head self-attention
- Feed-forward neural networks
- Positional encoding
- Output projection

**Why Transformers?**
- Parallel computation
- Long-context handling
- Better scalability than RNNs/LSTMs

---

### Types of Models

| Model Type | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| Base LLM | Pretrained on large-scale text data |
| Instruction-tuned | Optimized to follow commands |
| Chat Models | Multi-turn conversation handling |
| Embedding Models | Convert text into vectors |
| Multimodal Models | Text + image + audio |

---

### Training Pipeline
1. **Pre-training** – Self-supervised next-token prediction  
2. **Fine-tuning** – Task or domain-specific supervision  
3. **RLHF** – Reinforcement Learning with Human Feedback  

---

### Inference Parameters
- Temperature
- Top-K / Top-P sampling
- Max tokens
- Stop sequences

---

### Limitations
- Hallucinations
- Knowledge cutoff
- Context window limits
- No inherent fact verification

➡️ These limitations are addressed by the **Retrieval and Orchestration layers**.

---

## 2️⃣ Retrieval Layer (External Knowledge / Memory)

### Purpose
The **Retrieval Layer** enables the system to:
- Use private or proprietary data
- Access up-to-date information
- Reduce hallucinations
- Ground responses in facts

This layer enables **Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)**.

---

### RAG Flow
User Query
→ Convert to Embedding
→ Vector Database Search
→ Retrieve Relevant Context
→ Inject Context into Prompt
→ LLM Generates Answer

---

### Embeddings
- Dense vector representations of text
- Capture semantic meaning
- Enable similarity-based search

**Common similarity metrics:**
- Cosine similarity
- Dot product
- Euclidean distance

---

### Chunking Strategies

| Strategy | Use Case |
|--------|---------|
| Fixed-size | Simple documents |
| Overlapping chunks | Preserve context |
| Semantic chunking | Long PDFs, books |
| Sliding window | Conversation memory |

---

### Vector Databases
Used for storing and searching embeddings efficiently:
- Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN)
- Metadata filtering
- Horizontal scalability

**Vector DB vs SQL DB**
- SQL: exact match queries  
- Vector DB: semantic similarity search  

---

## 3️⃣ Orchestration Layer (Control & Intelligence)

### Purpose
The **Orchestration Layer** controls:
- Prompt construction
- Workflow execution
- Tool usage
- Memory handling
- Safety and validation

This is where **intelligence is engineered**, not trained.

---

### Prompt Engineering
Types:
- System prompts
- User prompts
- Few-shot examples
- Role-based prompts

Goals:
- Reduce hallucinations
- Enforce behavior
- Improve consistency

---

### Chains
Chains are **fixed, deterministic workflows**:
Input → Retrieval → LLM → Output

Used when:
- Flow is predictable
- Cost needs to be controlled

---

### Agents
Agents enable **dynamic decision-making**.

Agent loop:
Used when:
- Flow is predictable
- Cost needs to be controlled

---

### Agents
Agents enable **dynamic decision-making**.

Agent loop:
Think → Act → Observe → Repeat

Capabilities:
- Decide next step
- Call tools
- Iterate until goal completion

---

### Tool Calling
LLMs can call external tools such as:
- APIs
- Databases
- Calculators
- Code execution engines
- Web search services

The LLM outputs structured function calls instead of plain text.

---

### Memory Types

| Memory Type | Description |
|-----------|------------|
| Short-term | Current conversation |
| Long-term | User preferences |
| Episodic | Past interactions |
| Vector memory | Semantic recall |

---

### Safety & Guardrails
- Prompt injection prevention
- Output validation
- Schema enforcement
- Retry and fallback logic
- Toxicity filtering

---

## 4️⃣ Application Layer (Product & Infrastructure)

### Purpose
The **Application Layer**:
- Interfaces with users
- Handles authentication & security
- Scales the system
- Tracks cost and performance

---

### Frontend Responsibilities
- Chat UI
- Streaming responses
- Conversation history
- User feedback

---

### Backend Responsibilities
- API gateway
- Authentication (JWT / OAuth)
- Rate limiting
- Session management
- User context injection

---

### Observability
Key metrics:
- Token usage
- Latency
- Error rates
- Cost per request
- Hallucination frequency

---

### Security
- PII masking
- Encryption
- Role-based access control
- Prompt sanitization

---

### Deployment
- Docker containers
- Kubernetes orchestration
- Auto-scaling
- CI/CD pipelines
- Canary deployments

---

